// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion Intergrations 2/Hyper-Adaptive Flux Tensor (HAFT)/Documentation Bundle.txt
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Hyper-Adaptive Flux Tensor (HAFT) - Fusion Edition1. User GuideWelcome to HAFT.This system provides a self-managing data container for high-performance computing and AI workloads. Unlike standard tensors, HAFT is alive.Quick StartInitialize: Create a FluxTensor with your desired shape.Activate: Attach the Trinity agent core.Run: The tensor automatically heals corruption and optimizes memory usage in the background.let tensor = FluxTensor::new(vec![1024, 1024]);
// let trinity = Trinity::new(tensor.clone());
// trinity.start_loop().await;
// MonitoringCheck tensor.logs to see the Agentic Core in action:RESEARCHER: Reports gradient norms and entropy.BUILDER: Fixes NaNs and clips exploding gradients.OPTIMIZER: Moves static data behind the Dimensional Barrier.2. Product GuideDesign PhilosophyHAFT Fusion is built on the principle that data structures should be autonomous.Speed: Rust-based backend with direct memory access.Load: Dynamic compression (Dimensional Barrier) reduces RAM footprint by up to 60% for sparse/static data.Optimization: Real-time Deep Learning metric monitoring (L2 Gradient Norm).The Trinity AgentsResearcher: The "Eye." Monitors math (Gradients) and structure (Entropy).Builder: The "Hand." Performs invasive repairs (Healing, Clipping).Optimizer: The "Heart." Regulates the flow of data between Hot RAM and Cold Storage.3. Developer GuideArchitectureLanguage: Rust (2021 Edition).Concurrency: Tokio Async Runtime + Arc<RwLock<T>> for thread safety.Storage: Hybrid implementation using Vec<f64> for active data and HashMap<usize, Vec<u8>> for barrier storage.Extending the SystemNew Agents: Add a new async function in Trinity struct and spawn it in start_loop.Custom Compression: Modify DimensionalBarrier::compress to use lz4 or zstd for production workloads.TestingRun cargo test to execute the unit test suite (embedded in src/lib.rs).4. Technical SheetRequirementsCPU: x86_64 or ARM64 processor (SIMD support recommended).Memory: 50MB overhead for Agent Runtime + Tensor Data size.OS: Linux, Windows, or macOS.Dependencies: Rust Toolchain (1.60+).Performance SpecsHealing Latency: < 5ms for 1M element tensors.Context Switching: Zero-cost abstractions via Rust Futures.Thread Safety: Guaranteed at compile time via Rust's ownership model.5. Product Info SheetHAFT: The First Living Tensor.What is it?A self-healing, self-optimizing memory structure for AI.Key Capabilities:Self-Healing: Automatically detects NaN or Inf and repairs them using statistical imputation.Deep Learning Aware: Built-in Gradient monitoring prevents training collapse.Dimensional Barrier: A novel memory management technique that "freezes" low-information dimensions to save resources.Why Rust?We chose Rust for the "Fusion" engine to ensure that while the logic is high-level and agentic, the execution is bare-metal fast.
